BUAN 370 EXAMPLE PROJECT

Executive Summary

UberEats deliveries made made by our group member over the course of 6 months from June to December of 2021 in

both the Upper-Eastside Seattle and Greater San diego area.

The methods of analysis include exploratory by answering

questions of data distribution, variable correlation and relationships using the ggplot2 package in R.

This analysis also includes solving data queries that

provide a deeper understanding into some of the patterns that exist in the data.

Visualization 1: Final Pay Over Duration Of Trip (Line Chart)

Visualization 2: Average Promotion Per Day (Pie Chart)

Visualization 3: Average Pay Per Trip (Box Plot)

The average pay for a trip was ~$13. With the Interquartile Range in between $9 and $15.

Visualization 4: Distance and Duration compared to Final Pay

Matt is more likely to receive a bigger tip on Sundays rather than any of the other Day of the week. The second highest day of the week was Friday.

Visualization 6: Average Final pay vs Average Estimated pay by month

Queries

Query 1: Introduction to Variables

(All attributes with limit 5)

Query 2: Highest Paying Weekend Trips

Query 3: Days of the Week with the Highest Average Pay

Query 4 & 5: Highest Paying Trips on a Weekend and Weekday

Query 6 and 7: Trips With Additional Pay

Query 11: Average Pay and Tip based on Drop-off Location

Query 14: Total Additional Pay, Tip and Promotion

Conclusion

We learned that when dealing with queries related to money, it is most accurate to

take the average of these sums, and group them by another variable.

Pay. Our queries have shown the total amounts of money Matthew has gained

through fare, tips, promotion, and additional amounts. The total pay over all the trips was $5,702.28.

This information is very useful for Matthew when strategizing when and where to

take his trips, as well as for others to understand how drivers are compensated for their work.
